uss on the problem of science. Introducing us to Strauss's reflections on the meaning and perplexities of the scientific adventure, Svetozar Y. Minkov explores questions such as: Is there a human wisdom independent of science? What is the relation between poetry and mathematics, or between self-knowledge and theoretical physics? And how necessary is it for the human species to exist immutably in order for the classical analysis of human life to be correct? In pursuing these questions, Minkov aims to change the conversation about Strauss, one of the great thinkers of the past century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aNatural history. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Science. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846313140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438463131423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438463131/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles